Usually, we start talking and say, "Well,
the first thing they ask is,

00:17:09.030 --> 00:17:11.690
'Are you going to modify
my schema?'" It's like,

00:17:11.700 --> 00:17:16.440
"Don't touch my schema." That's
usually the way the IT people behave.

00:17:16.440 --> 00:17:17.100
That's fine.

00:17:17.150 --> 00:17:18.970
We've got no problem with that.

00:17:19.050 --> 00:17:20.680
We'll work both ways.

00:17:20.680 --> 00:17:25.820
We can put Xserves in there and basically
use the Xserve as a dual authentication.

00:17:25.820 --> 00:17:29.420
You're still authenticating
the user to Active Directory,

00:17:29.420 --> 00:17:32.150
but you're being managed
through the Xserve.

00:17:32.170 --> 00:17:35.080
That means that you don't have
to do any schema extension,

00:17:35.120 --> 00:17:39.640
and Eric will show you that
in the demo in a few minutes.

00:17:39.690 --> 00:17:40.360
That's the first way.

00:17:40.360 --> 00:17:42.320
You put an Xserve,
and you're basically still

00:17:42.320 --> 00:17:45.280
authenticating to AD,
but you're being managed through the

00:17:45.280 --> 00:17:47.400
Xserve using World Group Manager.

00:17:47.400 --> 00:17:51.190
The other way we can do it
is we can actually extend the

00:17:51.190 --> 00:17:53.720
schema on your Windows server.

00:17:53.720 --> 00:17:56.300
That's stuff that we also
do on the consulting side.

00:17:56.660 --> 00:17:59.400
